# Design Principles

These principles take precedence when making design and implementation decisions. Apply them in every code change.

## KISS — Keep It Simple

- Prefer the simplest solution that meets the requirement
- Avoid unnecessary abstractions, wrappers, or indirection layers
- If a feature can be achieved with fewer classes/files, do that
- Don't build frameworks when a function will do

## DRY — Don't Repeat Yourself

- Extract shared logic into helpers, extensions, or base classes when the same pattern appears 3+ times
- Use a shared helper when multiple blocks differ only in data (not structure)
- Don't DRY prematurely — two similar blocks are fine; three means extract

## SOLID

- **Single Responsibility**: Each class/widget does one thing. Split when a class has multiple reasons to change.
- **Open/Closed**: Prefer extending behaviour (e.g. new enum values, new subclasses) over modifying existing code.
- **Liskov Substitution**: Subtypes must be usable wherever their parent is expected.
- **Interface Segregation**: Widgets and functions should depend only on the data they actually use — don't pass an entire model when only two fields are needed.
- **Dependency Inversion**: Depend on abstractions (interfaces/abstract classes), not concrete implementations, especially in the data layer.

## YAGNI — You Aren't Gonna Need It

- Don't add code, parameters, or abstractions "just in case"
- Remove dead code (unused methods, getters, imports)
- Build what is required now; extend later when needed
